abstract: Sue Wilds Snyder, daughter of John A. Snyder of Darien, Conn., and the late Mrs. Snyder, was married yesterday to Edwin Ellis Flood Stebbins, son of Mrs. Andrew M. Blum of New York and James Flood Stebbins of Muttontown, L.I. The Rev. Frederick T. Bender performed the ceremony in St. Luke's Episcopal Church in Noroton, Conn.

abstract: Theodora K. Sklover was born in Brooklyn, where she dreamed of being a movie star. Nancy Littlefield was born in the Bronx, and grew up being more interested in what went on behind the camera. In tact, she later become the first female assistant director to be admitted to the Directors Guild of America.

abstract: Dr. Daniel Lerner, a sociologist, author and professor, died of cancer May 1 in Santa Cruz, Calif., where he had lived the last year. He was 62 years old.

abstract: WASHINGTON, May 7 (AP)--Soon after creating the Office of Education in the 1860's, Congress had second thoughts and demoted it to a bureau in the Department of Interior. Today it achieved full Cabinet status as the new Department of Education and celebrated its ascent with a ceremony on the South Lawn of the White House.
headline_main: Education Dept. Marks Cabinet Status; Secretary Makes Pledge 'Salute to Learning Day'
headline_print_headline: Education Dept. Marks Cabinet Status; Secretary Makes Pledge 'Salute to Learning Day'

abstract: WHEN Mary Sheehan and David Naka began planning their wedding earlier this year in Washington, her parents were expecting to pay for a formal wed  ding and a reception for more than 100 guests. But the longer the couple looked into the costs of a reception the more disenchanted they became with the idea of having her parents pay about $5,000 for an afternoon of food and drinks.
headline_main: A Break for the Father of the Bride; Father of the Bride Finally Gets a Break
